    story: `<p>Sindhupalchok District, covering 2,542 km² along the upper Indrawati and Melamchi river valleys, has been inhabited since antiquity by Tamang, Sherpa, Newar, and Brahmin communities whose temples and gompas punctuate every ridge. The Melamchi River—now famous for the Melamchi Water Supply Project that delivers water to Kathmandu—has for centuries been a pilgrimage and trade corridor between the Kathmandu Valley and Tibet.</p><p>The district was among the hardest hit by the April 2015 Gorkha Earthquake: entire villages like Barpak and Langtang were buried or destroyed. Today, rebuilt villages and quiet memorial sites around Sindhupalchok tell the story of resilience, with many communities constructing earthquake-resistant homes while preserving traditional Newari and Tibetan-influenced architecture. The Tatopani hot springs near the Chinese border and the Indreshwar Mahadev temple in Melamchi are important pilgrimage draws.</p><h3>Highlights</h3><ul><li>Melamchi River valley walks and village homestays</li><li>Indreshwar Mahadev Temple, one of the most sacred Shiva shrines in the region</li><li>Earthquake memorial sites and rebuilt resilient communities</li><li>Gateway to Panch Pokhari, Helambu, and Jugal Himal treks</li><li>Tatopani (hot springs) near the Nepal–Tibet border at Kodari</li></ul>`,
