    story: `<p>Perched in the remote Bhotang area of Sindhupalchok District at around 4,100 metres, Panch Pokhari has been a revered pilgrimage destination for centuries. According to Hindu tradition the five lakes correspond to the five Pandava brothers — Yudhishthira, Bhima, Arjuna, Nakula, and Sahadeva — who meditated here during their exile in the Mahabharata. Buddhists equally venerate the site, and mani walls, prayer flags, and a small gompa at the lakeside bear witness to its dual spiritual identity.</p><p>The most spectacular time to visit is Janai Purnima (the full moon of Shrawan, usually August), when thousands of Hindu pilgrims make a barefoot overnight trek to bathe in the icy glacial waters, believing this purifies the soul and allows the annual sacred thread (janai) to be renewed. Buddhist devotees circle the lakes in meditation. For most of the year, however, the site is peacefully empty, accessible only to committed trekkers willing to endure steep ascents of 500–800 m per day.</p><h3>Highlights</h3><ul><li>Five sacred alpine glacial lakes at 4,100 m within Langtang National Park</li><li>Janai Purnima pilgrimage festival in August — one of Nepal's most dramatic high-altitude festivals</li><li>360-degree panorama of Jugal Himal, Langtang range, and surrounding peaks</li><li>Rich rhododendron and bamboo forests on the approach trail</li><li>Small Buddhist gompa and ancient mani walls beside the lakes</li></ul>`,
