    story: `<p>Helambu — also called Yolmo — is a highland valley and cultural zone stretching north from the rim of the Kathmandu Valley into the lower flanks of the Jugal and Langtang massifs. The people of Helambu, known as Hyolmo or Sherpa, maintain a rich tradition of Tibetan Buddhism: gompas with painted murals, prayer-flag-draped ridges, and chortens line the trail. The trek begins at Sundarijal on the northeastern edge of Kathmandu, passes through Shivapuri National Park, and ascends to the high ridge at Chisapani before descending into the valley proper.</p><p>The route threads through villages like Kutumsang, Mangengoth, Tharepati (the highest point at 3,690 m), Tarke Gyang — the largest settlement in Helambu — and Sermathang, before dropping to Melamchi Bazaar in Sindhupalchok. Each village offers a window into a way of life little changed for centuries: yak cheese making, hand-woven textiles, and Buddhist monastery ceremonies. The forests burst into colour during spring with blooming rhododendrons of pink, red, and white.</p><h3>Highlights</h3><ul><li>Tharepati ridge (3,690 m) with sweeping views of Jugal Himal and Langtang peaks</li><li>Tarke Gyang gompa — the spiritual heart of the Helambu region</li><li>Dense rhododendron and oak forests through Shivapuri National Park</li><li>Authentic Hyolmo (Sherpa) village culture and Buddhist monasteries</li><li>Chisapani viewpoint with sunrise panoramas over the Kathmandu Valley</li><li>Relative solitude compared to Everest and Annapurna circuits</li></ul>`,
