    summary: "The Langtang Valley Trek is one of Nepal's most celebrated short-to-medium treks, following the Langtang River deep into a glaciated valley flanked by Langtang Lirung (7,227 m) and a wall of Himalayan giants just south of the Tibetan border. The standard 8-day route from Syabrubesi passes Lama Hotel, the rebuilt Langtang Village, and Kyanjin Gompa at 3,870 m \u2014 home to a famous yak cheese factory and the optional ascent of Tserko Ri at 4,984 m. The valley lies entirely within Langtang National Park.",
    story: `<p>Langtang Valley was Nepal's 'third most popular trekking region' before April 2015, when a catastrophic earthquake-triggered avalanche obliterated Langtang Village, killing more than 350 people. The rebuilt village now stands as a testament to Tamang resilience, with new stone houses, a rebuilt gompa, and a growing memorial site for those who perished. The road to recovery has slowly brought trekkers back, and the valley's raw, uncrowded beauty — rated by many as the finest in Nepal for scenery per day of walking — rewards those who make the journey.</p><p>Leaving Syabrubesi (1,460 m), the trail climbs through semi-tropical forest to Lama Hotel (2,470 m), then ascends the dramatic U-shaped glacial valley past waterfalls and cliffs patrolled by grey langur monkeys and red pandas. Langtang Village (3,430 m) and Kyanjin Gompa (3,870 m) sit beneath an almost vertical wall of ice: Langtang Lirung rises over 3,000 m in a single sweep from the valley floor. The Kyanjin cheese factory, established by the Swiss Development Corporation in the 1950s, still produces yak cheese you can taste and buy.</p><h3>Highlights</h3><ul><li>Kyanjin Gompa and 360° Himalayan views from Tserko Ri (4,984 m)</li><li>Langtang Lirung (7,227 m) and Kimshung glacier views</li><li>Yak cheese factory at Kyanjin — a unique tasting experience</li><li>Rebuilt Langtang Village and earthquake memorial site</li><li>Rich wildlife: red panda, snow leopard, Himalayan tahr</li><li>Tamang village culture, mani walls, and Buddhist monasteries</li></ul>`,
