    story: `<p>Sundarijal — meaning 'beautiful water' in Nepali — lives up to its name with a striking waterfall that plunges down a rocky gorge flanked by dense forest on the northeastern rim of the Kathmandu Valley. The area has been designated part of Shivapuri Nagarjun National Park, protecting its watershed function and the rich biodiversity of its subtropical and temperate forest zones. For generations, Kathmandu residents have made day trips here to picnic, bathe, and escape the capital's dust and noise.</p><p>Beyond the waterfall, Sundarijal is Nepal's most convenient trek starting point: within 30 minutes of reaching the village from the city, trekkers can be on forest trails that within a day ascend to Chisapani ridge with sweeping Himalayan sunrise views. The trail continues into the Helambu region and can connect with the Langtang circuit via Gosaikunda. The national park entry checkpoint here also marks the boundary of the protected watershed that feeds the Sundarijal water treatment plant, which supplies roughly a third of Kathmandu's drinking water.</p><h3>Highlights</h3><ul><li>Sundarijal Waterfall — dramatic cascade in a forested gorge</li><li>Trailhead for Helambu, Chisapani, and Gosaikunda treks</li><li>Shivapuri Nagarjun National Park wildlife and birdwatching</li><li>Kathmandu Valley viewpoint from Chisapani (2,165 m) within a day's hike</li><li>Easy 30–45 minute drive from central Kathmandu</li></ul>`,
