    story: `<p>The Manaslu Circuit remained off-limits to foreign trekkers until 1991, and its restricted-area status — requiring a special permit and a minimum group of two with a licensed guide — has kept it blessedly crowd-free compared to Nepal's other classic circuits. The route begins at Machha Khola (869 m) after a long drive from Gorkha, then follows the great gorge of the Budhi Gandaki for days through subtropical jungle, suspension bridges, and waterfalls before the landscape opens into the high Himalayan zone. The village of Samagaun (3,520 m) serves as a rest and acclimatization day, with an optional side trek to Manaslu Base Camp (4,800 m) beneath the icy south face of Manaslu itself.</p><p>The physical and emotional climax is the crossing of Larkya La Pass (5,106 m): a pre-dawn start from Dharamsala (4,470 m) through moraine and glacier leads to the windswept col, from which the panorama of Himlung (7,126 m), Kanguru (6,981 m), Annapurna II (7,937 m), and dozens of other giants unfolds. The descent into the Annapurna zone feels like entering a different world — greener, warmer, and busier. Most trekkers complete the circuit by exiting at Dharapani and driving to Pokhara or Kathmandu.</p><h3>Highlights</h3><ul><li>Larkya La Pass (5,106 m) — the dramatic high-altitude crossing</li><li>Manaslu Base Camp optional day trip from Samagaun</li><li>Budhi Gandaki gorge — one of Nepal's deepest and most scenic river canyons</li><li>Tibetan-Buddhist villages of Lho, Samagaun, and Samdo with ancient gompas</li><li>Views of Manaslu (8,163 m), Ganesh Himal, and Annapurna ranges</li><li>Red-panda habitat and rich alpine wildlife</li><li>Restricted area status ensuring low trekker density</li></ul>`,
