    name: "Gorkha Durbar",
    category: "DURBAR_PALACE",
    summary: "Gorkha Durbar is a magnificent hilltop palace-fortress complex in Gorkha town, Gandaki Province, built in the 16th century and birthplace of Prithvi Narayan Shah (1723\u20131775), the founder-king who unified Nepal. Perched at approximately 1,650 m on a dramatic ridge with sweeping views of the Himalayan range from Dhaulagiri to Manaslu, the complex blends palace, fortress, and temple in superb Newari architecture. It was partially damaged in the 2015 earthquake and restored, reopening in 2023.",
    story: `<p>Gorkha Durbar stands on a sharp sandstone ridge rising above Gorkha Bazaar, and for several centuries it was the nerve centre of the Gorkha kingdom — the small mountain principality from which Prithvi Narayan Shah launched his ambitious campaign to unify the fractious kingdoms of the Kathmandu Valley and beyond. Construction of the original palace is attributed to Ram Shah in the early 17th century, but it was Prithvi Narayan Shah, born here in 1723, who transformed Gorkha into the seat of a new Nepal. The climb of roughly 1,500 steep stone steps from the bazaar, or a shorter jeep route, arrives at a complex of temples, courtyards, and the royal chambers where Nepal's unification was planned.</p><p>The Gorakhkali Mandir inside the palace complex houses the goddess Kali and the shrine of Gorakhnath, the patron saint of the Gorkha rulers, from whom both the royal house and the famous Gurkha soldiers drew their name and identity. Non-Hindus may view the exterior of the inner shrine but not enter it. The palace suffered significant damage in the April 2015 earthquake, which caused masonry walls to collapse and the main tower to crack; extensive restoration by the Department of Archaeology, with support from international heritage partners, brought the complex back to visitors in late 2023.</p><h3>Highlights</h3><ul><li>Birthplace of Prithvi Narayan Shah — founding king of unified Nepal</li><li>Gorakhkali and Gorakhnath shrines with active religious rituals</li><li>Panoramic Himalayan views: Manaslu, Himlung, Annapurna range</li><li>Exceptional Newari woodcarving on windows, struts, and doors</li><li>Archaeological Museum of Gorkha with royal artifacts and coins</li><li>1,500-step stone stairway through rhododendron forest</li></ul>`,
