    name: "Tatopani Hot Springs",
    category: "HOT_SPRING",
    summary: "Tatopani \u2014 meaning 'hot water' \u2014 is a small village at 1,190 m on the Kali Gandaki River in Myagdi District (Mustang border area), famous for its natural geothermal hot spring pools that soothe weary muscles on the Annapurna Circuit. The hot springs at the confluence of the Kali Gandaki and Ghar Khola rivers are considered sacred, and the village has historically been an important stop for traders, pilgrims, and trekkers alike. Surrounded by orange and banana groves, it offers a lush microclimate in contrast to the high alpine terrain above.",
    story: `<p>Tatopani sits in one of the deepest river gorges on Earth — the Kali Gandaki corridor between Dhaulagiri and Annapurna creates the world's deepest valley measured from peak to river. At 1,190 m, Tatopani is dramatically warmer and lusher than the austere high-altitude terrain of the Annapurna Circuit above it, with terraced orange orchards and subtropical vegetation thriving in the sheltered gorge microclimate. The hot springs bubble up naturally at the bank of the Kali Gandaki, channelled into concrete pools where trekkers, pilgrims, and locals soak together in mineral-rich water reputed to ease joint pain and altitude-related fatigue.</p><p>Since the opening of the Beni–Jomsom motor road, Tatopani has become easily accessible by jeep from Beni, and many trekkers now use it as either a starting or ending point for treks into the Annapurna region. The village itself is a pleasant mix of Thakali guesthouses, small restaurants, and orchards. A significant annual fair draws pilgrims who make a ritual bath in the hot springs during major Hindu festivals. From Tatopani, the trail climbs steeply to Ghorepani and the famous Poon Hill sunrise viewpoint — making it a popular base for the Ghorepani–Poon Hill circuit as well as the longer Annapurna Circuit.</p><h3>Highlights</h3><ul><li>Natural geothermal hot spring pools at the Kali Gandaki riverside</li><li>Gateway to Ghorepani–Poon Hill trek (steep 1,700 m ascent)</li><li>Deepest river valley in the world — Kali Gandaki gorge between Dhaulagiri and Annapurna</li><li>Lush sub-tropical microclimate with orange, lemon, and banana trees</li><li>Thakali cuisine and traditional guesthouses</li><li>Sacred bathing festival during major Hindu holidays</li></ul>`,
