    name: "Bhaktapur Pottery Square",
    category: "CULTURAL_VILLAGE",
    summary: "Bhaktapur Pottery Square (Bolachha Tole / Kumha Tole) is a living open-air workshop in the heart of Bhaktapur city where Newar potters have practiced their craft for generations, shaping clay vessels on traditional foot-powered wheels in full view of visitors. The square is covered in drying pots, terracotta wares, and sacred items for festivals, using the unique black clay \u2014 called 'Dyo Cha' or 'clay of God' \u2014 that gives Bhaktapur pottery its distinctive quality and colour. It remains one of the most authentic artisan traditions in the Kathmandu Valley.",
    story: `<p>A short walk south of Bhaktapur Durbar Square, Bolachha Tole has been the domain of the Kumha (potter) caste for as long as Bhaktapur has existed. The square is not a museum or a performance — it is a working neighbourhood where terracotta production is the primary livelihood. Each morning, potters arrive to knead black clay (dug from specific fields blessed by tradition) and spin it into vases, water pots, temple oil lamps, and ritual funeral pots. The wet forms are arranged across every flat surface to dry in the sun before firing in the communal kilns that stand at the square's edges.</p><p>The craft holds deep religious significance in Nepal: Bhaktapur's potters supply terracotta wares for festivals across the Kathmandu Valley, including the massive Bisket Jatra and Indra Jatra celebrations that require hundreds of specially shaped clay vessels. The Bhaktapur Pottery Training Centre on the square's edge offers hands-on sessions where visitors can learn basic wheel-throwing techniques and take their creation home. Bhaktapur's ceramics are considered superior across the valley because of the exceptional quality of its local black clay, which fires to a warm reddish-black with excellent structural integrity.</p><h3>Highlights</h3><ul><li>Working terracotta workshop — watch master potters at foot-powered wheels</li><li>Try pottery-making yourself at the training centre (NPR 100–150)</li><li>Traditional firing kilns and outdoor drying grounds</li><li>Unique 'Dyo Cha' black clay tradition of Bhaktapur</li><li>Festival supply production — see ritual wares for Bisket Jatra</li><li>Small temples and chaityas within the square</li></ul>`,
